window.docContents[239].resolve({"/Elementary-Number-Theory/Sums-of-squares-and-Pythagorean-triples/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elementary-Number-Theory--Sums-of-squares-and-Pythagorean-triples--Lagrange___s-Four-Square-Theorem":{"contents":"(Lagrange's four-square theorem.) Every natural number  is a sum of four squares: there exist naturals  with\n\n\nBy Euler's identity () the sums of four squares are closed under multiplication, so by induction on the factorization of  (the multiplicative recursion: , , primes, and products) it suffices to represent each prime .For a prime , mathlib runs Fermat's infinite descent. First, the same kind of residue-counting that underlies the two-square theorem () — a pigeonhole over the  squares — produces  and  with , so some positive multiple  is a sum of four squares. Take the least such . If , one descends: when  is even one halves it using the identity, and when  is odd one replaces  by their least-absolute-value representatives modulo , obtaining via Euler's identity a representation of  with , contradicting minimality. Hence the least  is  and  itself is a sum of four squares.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Elementary Number Theory\u0009Sums of squares and Pythagorean triples","header":"1.5.3. Lagrange's Four-Square Theorem","id":"/Elementary-Number-Theory/Sums-of-squares-and-Pythagorean-triples/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elementary-Number-Theory--Sums-of-squares-and-Pythagorean-triples--Lagrange___s-Four-Square-Theorem"},"/Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry/Weierstrass-equations-and-the-discriminant/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry--Weierstrass-equations-and-the-discriminant--Elliptic-Curves":{"contents":"A Weierstrass curve  over  is elliptic if its discriminant \n() is a unit in . In mathlib this is the typeclass\nWeierstrassCurve.IsElliptic, a one-field class asserting IsUnit W.Δ; over a field it is\nequivalent to , i.e. nonsingularity of the cubic. When  is elliptic one\nwrites  for the chosen unit lifting  (WeierstrassCurve.Δ').\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Elliptic Curves and Arithmetic Geometry\u0009Weierstrass equations and the discriminant","header":"7.1.5. Elliptic Curves","id":"/Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry/Weierstrass-equations-and-the-discriminant/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry--Weierstrass-equations-and-the-discriminant--Elliptic-Curves"},"/Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms/Results-from-the-LeanModularForms-project/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms--Results-from-the-LeanModularForms-project--The-Atkin-Lehner-main-lemma":{"contents":"Atkin–Lehner Main Lemma (Miyake 4.6.8 / Diamond–Shurman 5.7.1).\nLet  be a cusp form whose Fourier coefficients vanish at all indices\ncoprime to the level,\n\nThen  is an oldform: .\nFormalised in LeanModularForms: proved sorry-free\nvia Miyake's descent in the SMOObligations files and packaged as HeckeRing.GL2.oldPart_eq_zero_of_shared_eigenvalues. (The alternative Petersson-adjoint route HeckeRing.GL2.mainLemma remains a sorry, but strong multiplicity one does not use it.)Depends on:   \n\nThe formalised proof avoids the Petersson adjoint entirely and instead descends, following Miyake\n§4.6. Suppose  is a common eigenfunction with all coprime Fourier coefficients vanishing. For\neach prime , a descent witness lowers  to a cusp form  at level\n whose coprime coefficients reproduce those of  at shifted indices; iterating across the\nprime factors of  exhibits  as built from forms genuinely of lower level. Concretely, the\nmatching-summand construction produces, whenever the new part were nonzero, a nonzero new eigenform\n at a proper divisor  whose eigenvalues match 's; its leading coefficient is\nnonzero (), and  then has vanishing coprime\ncoefficients, forcing  itself into the old subspace — i.e. . This is\nsorry-free; the spectral/adjoint inputs that the alternative proof would need are sidestepped.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Modular and Automorphic Forms\u0009Results from the LeanModularForms project","header":"6.8.10. The Atkin-Lehner main lemma","id":"/Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms/Results-from-the-LeanModularForms-project/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms--Results-from-the-LeanModularForms-project--The-Atkin-Lehner-main-lemma"},"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/Forthcoming-in-mathlib/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces--Forthcoming-in-mathlib--The-Amice-transform-and-Amice-equivalence":{"contents":"(Amice transform / Amice equivalence.) The Amice transform sends a -adic measure  on\n () — equivalently a bounded -valued\ndistribution — to the power series\n\nwhose coefficients are exactly the moments of  against the Mahler basis ().\nThe Amice equivalence is the resulting isomorphism of -Banach algebras\n()\n\nbetween measures on  and bounded power series, under which convolution corresponds to\nmultiplication.PR #23772 (with companion #23791) constructs the Amice transform and proves it an isomorphism, the\nanalytic foundation for -adic -functions and Iwasawa theory; it builds directly on Mahler's\ntheorem ().\nIn review — mathlib PR #23772.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009p-adic and Adic Spaces\u0009Forthcoming in mathlib","header":"5.16.1. The Amice transform and Amice equivalence","id":"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/Forthcoming-in-mathlib/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces--Forthcoming-in-mathlib--The-Amice-transform-and-Amice-equivalence"}});